A Republican strategy to stall the re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, considers the latter a myth and claims that voter fraud is less prevalent in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only found 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In that sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
And along the same lines, a majority of American governments, starting in 2009, enacted new laws that made it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon has spread after the November 2010 elections, which saw the rise of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of voting rights were introduced in 41 states during 2011.
The new election laws require voters to present a photo ID, as well as proof of U.S. citizenship.
On the other hand, these laws reduce early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as an elector on polling day and strip citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no American state required voters to present a photo ID.
The state of Indiana was the first to demand it.
The U.S. Supreme Court in 2008 upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law.
The Republican authorities therefore hurried to extend the practice to other states.
In recent years, these authorities have supported bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity document, such as a Social Security card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, don't have any photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
On the other hand, five million new voters in 2012 lack an identity document with these characteristics.
But often it costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity document.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000 a year, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have a photo ID.
And there's more.
In many states, students, the voters who vote most heavily for Democratic candidates, are not allowed to use the photo ID issued by their institution.
Moreover, those same States authorise members of fishing or hunting clubs who usually vote for the Republican parties to use the documents issued by those clubs.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to file such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are American citizens.
Those measures clearly seek to limit the Hispanic vote.
It seems like two out of three Hispanic voters support the Democratic Party.
On the other hand, Republican lawmakers backed in 2011 certain laws that abolished voter registration on the same day of the ballot in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to create a help service to voters who wanted to register.
These restrictions have consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns contributed to the registration of about 10 million citizens.
The measures taken since 2009 have led to a fall in the rate of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states passed laws that favored shortening the advance voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida elections, 33% of the voters who voted early were African-American, while the latter represented no more than 13% of the state's electors.
The same thing happened with the Hispanics.
They represent only 11% of the electorate, which is equivalent to 24% of the citizens who vote in advance.
However, whites, who represent 76% of the electorate, represent no more than 46% of the citizens who vote in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have vehemently opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
In this regard, Democratic governors have blocked several bills.
The U.S. Attorney's Office intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
Some damage was contained.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed a law requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, it is undeniable that the new rules adopted will complicate the exercise of the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been voted, as it is clear that they are intended to influence the results of 2012 in the key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that have adopted such laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty whether these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, the measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
