The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a huge stir last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what's more, it's the particle whose existence the Standard Model predicted: our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has yet to be observed empirically.
But it's not entirely clear to physicists that it's the Higgs.
We know beyond a shadow of a doubt that a new particle exists and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference held in Kyoto seems to confirm that it is, although more data is still needed to be completely certain.
Anyway, we assume that this is the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim.
There is, in this great world, a universal and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break that rule, and don't try too hard, because you'll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is a law of these characteristics in it as well: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly speaking, of some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
And then there are the bosons, a bunch of dirty anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of Berkeley Laboratories, which is quite extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, I should stress here, are not the exotic beasts that we might think.
In fact, if you can read this account, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon, or "particle of light", that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In effect, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that particular environment - much like throwing a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (from light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it's another field, the Higgs field, that needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
Now, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field, and to activate it, you have to reach extremely high energies, a bit like a frozen pond in which only a thick rock could slide across the surface.
This is why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN's (the Large Hadron Collider is a 27 km circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
The electromagnetic field analogy is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick to a refrigerator door by itself.
And similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what "can all this research do?" asks Mrs Plamondon.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the standard model (SM), and further allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between observations and SM predictions.
Many, for their part, are eager to meet, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that would plug certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation relating to gravity (ups!) or to dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter of the Universe (another ups!).
But we haven't found such differences at CERN so far.
The aftermath
The implications of such research on our daily lives are difficult to predict, but let us not think that we are wrong in saying that it will have none.
So let me show you: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the laboratories had no idea of the revolution that their work would bring about.
They were looking at scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was considered more of a "laboratory device".
I mean, imagine that.
And furthermore, applications can also come from all the instrumentation surrounding the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light-sensing device in 1969 in the course of his research on optics.
Although it was by no means his original intention, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
That's not to say, of course, that the activities of the LHC are necessarily going to transform our lives, but you never know...
