With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
This is the opposite of today's monetary exchanges, which are based on central banks, identified transactions and processing charges between parties.
Moreover, as is often the case with technologies, the political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, composed of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency convertible to dollars, euros, etc. and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from peer to peer.
Nearly 200,000 transactions have been recorded thanks to 15,000 computers on the network.
And about a thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com page).
It's not that impressive compared to the global changes in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in him in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It described bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other systems with types of virtual currencies such as "credits", used to advance in a video game and which can be earned by playing or can be bought (and even sometimes redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange, a central authority controls and deals with the exchanges.
With bitcoin, all nodes of the network are at once bookkeepers, verifiers, coin issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does that network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually done between two email addresses in the form of an email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus guaranteeing anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a double-key encryption system.
The network can then verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file's content, it's also possible to ensure that bitcoin's changes are recorded in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This involves solving a mathematical challenge thrown to the computers and the winner, a sort of provisional central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a file-sharing phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
The computers "make" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular imprint (more zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it's the good one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If, in order to commit fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept one of the two transactions as valid; the other would be left as an orphan, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is regularly halved, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to the hundred millionth, which leaves a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed with each increase in computing power.
Life on the network has its ups and downs.
Websites offering services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
"The fault used does not affect the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes account of the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Big players like Wikipedia reject payments of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, the "giant rebates" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars changed", rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a textbook on the currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology, as well as in the transaction network.
Their system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The wearer also manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to implement in shops, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They simply provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to take hold, but in 2013 there could be a change", he predicts.
The ECB also envisages in its report a reassessment of the various risks, now considered high, in the event of the success of this currency.
