A Constitution with force in Egypt
He is a new double or nothing of President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever about the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants him full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
He took everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when he announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Only a week ago the Head of State gave the Assembly two more months to finish its work.
And for almost two years now, Egypt has been using an interim text, modified several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial muddle.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his "autocratic delirium" and continues to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
The Commission is also proposing to extend the deadline for the submission of proposals to the Council for a decision on the application of the new rules to the Commission.
A referendum should be held within the next two weeks.
A very short time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote for him, as he claimed in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this appeal was voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "either you vote for my text or I retain full powers", powers that are supposed to end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, the vast majority of whom are Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals didn't show up for the call.
By mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people were added yesterday morning, as substitutes, in a hurry.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As might be expected, the articles voted on were unanimous.
Commentators are also pleased that one of the few discrepancies of the day was expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the Constituent Assembly's clock was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday evening, comprises 234 articles.
Article 2, the object of all eyes, is finally identical to the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that "the principles of the Sharia constitute the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that "principles" could be replaced by "norms", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been modified is a guarantee of their goodwill and of their respect towards the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it to be nothing more than a publicity stunt.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University a consultative role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, it is worrying because "the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy".
The liberals' fears are further heightened by the fact that the university's next rector would be far less moderate than the current one.
"At this time, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not scholars but university students, some of them trained in the French system", explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used mimic religious vocabulary.
"We refer specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ed].
And the question that might be asked in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule on all this".
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms concerning the extended powers it confers on the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in number compared to what they were under the previous regime.
Another point of contention is the powers conferred on the army.
As the military wishes, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as human rights associations have called for.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy remains, and from now on insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article emphasizes the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
The only positive thing, she said, was the prohibition of torture under Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
