According to an ancient legend, the mountain's summit was supposedly inhabited by pagan gods.
Visiting unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can't visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them are worth visiting, the most interesting ones.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Israeli Parliament).
It houses the ancient Dead Sea Scrolls, or Qumran Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological items.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is worth a visit.
In its exhibition of paintings it has canvases by impressionists and expressionists such as Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall or Picasso.
In Acre you can visit the museum-bath Al Basha, which are some rooms of ancient Turkish baths with model figures of visitors and bathers of that time.
In Caesarea, it is worthwhile to visit the exclusive private museum Ralli, where you can admire the sculptures of Rodin and Dalí.
There are no tourist guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free, and donations are categorically not accepted.
The fifth, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, shows one of the most dramatic pages in history.
The most tragic section is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
