Ukraine is mentioned as well.
Health
Israel's three main tourist areas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of these is home to swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and oceanographic museums.
It is curious that the Red Sea is bathed even in the winter months, since the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and they bathe there all year round.
By the way, this sea, the most extraordinary in the world, is located at the lowest point on the planet: 417 meters below sea level.
The blue waters there are a brackish water that easily supports even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes around here are truly beautiful.
People come here to undergo courses of treatment with salt water, brine and curative mud and to fortify their health in cases of dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to put in order their broken nerves.
Playing the mysteries of antiquity
They are preserved in the old part of Tel Aviv, the citadel of Jaffa, on the Mediterranean coast.
It was the famous sea route linking Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus rescued the beautiful Andromeda with whom, in this very spot, he led a long and happy life.
Tourists love to stroll along the narrow streets named after the signs of the zodiac.
They say if you touch the walls in the street of your "same" symbol, fortune will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa you can find newlywed couples who come from all over Israel, and even from other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "take" the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the chief city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The theater, carefully restored, is now used for night concerts and opera performances.
