Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed home.
Since December 1 a law has been in force, according to which every immigrant worker must take an examination to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those intending to work in the service sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, in time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
It is not enough to pass the language test, but also the Russian history and the legal foundations test.
The knowledge of the language must be confirmed even for the purpose of obtaining and renewing the work permit.
The only exceptions are citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
This law will not apply to persons who obtained their educational certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991.
Usefulness, fatality and defence of rights
The network of examination centres will be operated under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, there are more than 160 such centres open in Russia right now.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the State Duma deputies and by the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights defenders, long before the law came into force, often managed to ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the compulsory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for the immigrants themselves?
First, respond the representatives of the Immigration Service, this will allow to reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
