The defence of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organised selection system will solve the problem of migrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are the immigrants without a profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass the medical check.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev claims, the future immigrant will be condemned to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, will put him on a "paid trip" to a creepy and narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him consume for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but on arrival they are deceived, deprived of their passports, not paid the promised salaries", confirms the Head of the Directorate of labor immigration of the Tajikistan immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, little chief!
However, in the meantime, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the country to which they intend to go, but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as it is their own misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive a normal primary education.
This is because their families have nothing to even feed the children, let alone dress them, shoe them and buy them school supplies.
As they reach adolescence, these boys venture into work at the first opportunity.
It's hard, if you don't know the language, to recognize them.
"One feels humiliated and inferior".
However, when it comes to the language law, rights advocates point out an important point.
The tests will be carried out only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
