"For now, fooling the brain is not so easy"
The subject of augmented reality, which is so popular among lovers of modern technology, is lately seen mainly through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer, Google demonstrated a moving model at its annual conference and then, in November, it became known that Microsoft had also filed an application to claim the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the 3D interactive technology group at Microsoft's Cambridge lab, Izadi Sharamom, it became clear that for the company's scientists, the glasses were already a thing of the past.
They are attracted to the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please, in general terms, what is the object of study of your research group?
- We are dedicated to human-computer interaction, but we also try to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
For now, humanity in its mass has been caught in the stage of working with the pixels of the flat screen, sometimes touching it with the finger.
But we want to look five to 10 years ahead and guess the cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors represent a step forward and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else does the future hold?
- Even though Kinect has taken interaction to the physical level, much of it still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), and the output is still not very good.
We're trying to change that, we're working on truly three-dimensional visualization systems, based on different technologies, including design.
It must free the world from the computer to our world, the physical, make it more tangible.
For this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user but also the space around him.
Then we can complement the real world with virtual objects in a more comfortable way.
First of all, to hell with those silly VR headsets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A very popular detail, but don't you think it's overrated?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea, the issue of privacy remains to be resolved, since we do not always want others to know about our actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of computer interaction are good, but each in its own field.
For example, for the control of devices in public places, we had a project where we thought about gestures, but not in single movements, but shorter ones.
Moreover, the gestures were captured not by the device's camera but by a wristband that recorded the movement of the bones and muscles.
It's very large right now, but in theory it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future is for a combined type of control, for example gesture + voice.
- How's that?
- For example, how would you ask me to pass this soda can?
You will speak and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that's gonna be very hard to recognize.
- So, you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot do at this point?
- Not necessarily, but it's a mutual approach.
I think in the near future we're going to have to work primarily on designing new kinds of sensors that can accurately measure the reactions of the person.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, as they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
- Speaking of your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what complaints do you have about modern cameras?
Do they lack resolution, depth, or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what may be the beginning of our work with three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at the rate of 1000 fps.
But the question is not megapixels, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this last point of view, all the current technologies are not good enough for us; this gives more work to the algorithm designers.
So we have to remember not just the resolution on the X and Y axes, but also on the Z axis.
Speed is also important, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic and the current 30 fps are really scarce, especially for gestures.
Steven Bathiche, from our laboratory in Redmond, made a contact sensor with adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100 ms and it should be mentioned that modern mass-produced sensors are closer to the second value (60-100).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
I'd be very useful for my work with an equivalent of such a device, but one that doesn't require contact so that the frames per second are more.
- And there's no need to increase the number of cameras?
- The Kinect now has three "cameras", one of which is actually the infrared emitter and the second is the reflected signal receiver.
But the third camera is actually a simple visible tuning fork sensor.
It is not used to determine the depth of the object.
Potentially, more cameras could solve the problem...
Or, on the contrary, increase it and increase the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible Kinect analog, play with the curvature of the cameras' location and see how this would help determine the three-dimensional position.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, has not introduced its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that from the point of view of the everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most visible platforms?
- Of course, to spend all the time holding high a smartphone in the hands, is not very comfortable, but I think: the best option would be a "transmutable" augmented reality when, based on a cloud platform, you could go from glasses to a smartphone,
Glasses are very personal devices, that's their strength (private things only you can see), but also their weakness: an augmented reality based on glasses will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Let's imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from the movie "Iron Man", but also to any ordinary mortal.
There's a problem with this idea that critics often point out: there's no tactile response!
The hands don't feel anything!
What responses does your group prepare for this challenge?
- In my lectures I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the octave might well be the addition of tactile sensation.
Meanwhile, one of the most interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a support for the image.
Record the touch perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really geared to add tangible to these "airborne images". For example, the interference of several ultrasonic rays directed at a specific point where the finger is located gives a sensation similar to that you would feel if someone were blowing into your fingertips, but that sensation is still very weak.
There are also wrist bracelets that influence the nerve endings of the fingers, this too a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he thinks he should feel the moment he sees something?
- That's a good idea, we haven't tried it yet.
Here is another challenge that we will have to fight for a long time, how to make a person physically located in a very small space believe that he is going to an open space, almost without end. We are also working on the idea of treadmills (not like those of gyms), mobile platforms, as well as the giant balloons.
For now, fooling the brain is not so easy, it still has to work for many years.
That's what makes working with virtual reality so appealing to researchers, that many things are in a state of full conception.
