Earth is in danger.
Global warming or a collision with a killer asteroid.
Spacecraft convoys with humans on board are off in search of a spare planet.
To preserve humanity, the main question is: How to continue the species in sterile conditions or on the same spare planet?
I think there's not much to choose from.
In fact, only two are actual planets that can be colonized, at least hypothetically.
"These are Venus and Mars", says the chief researcher of the State Institute of Astronomy, Sternberg P.K. (IAES), Vladimir Surdin.
But if conditions on Mars are better for life, on the surface of Venus the temperature is 500 degrees.
It can only live at high altitudes or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
The problems of reproduction in space with flora were addressed.
Experiments with plants have been going on for half a century.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from the terrestrial varieties.
Then came the brood of insects in orbit, the little fruit flies, the drosophilus.
In 1979 quail eggs were sent into space to see how the embryo develops in the weightless environment.
The result is a normal chick.
But then the problems start.
"The problem is that the chick has to find support, stand on its own feet and start moving", explains Vladimir Sychev, the laboratory director of the Institute of Biomedical Problems (IPBM) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Unable to find support, the chicks flipped randomly.
And after 10 hours in the newborns there was a total atrophy of the instincts.
The chicks didn't react to light or sound.
And the misfortune was that after four days they simply died.
"And twice we managed to get the chicks to hatch, but then we left because it was impossible to work with them there", says Vladimir Sychev about the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last time a biological "mini-arch" flew into orbit was 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
However, only species of the same sex will travel on the Bion biosatellite.
There was an experiment with rats, who were sent into space already with fetuses.
