At the meeting of the Control Committee in the Congress of Deputies you spoke of the joint project between the Czech and German teams, in which the legislation on public procurement in both countries was compared.
What is it exactly?
This is a parallel control that we started to do about two years ago.
Simply put, European legislation regulates how public tenders should be organised, followed by the legislation in force in each country and then by the practice itself.
We have put it all together and, although the control is not yet complete, we have obtained very interesting differences.
It is therefore confirmed that it is not enough to incorporate increasingly strict rules, but that it is necessary to concentrate on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually bring? What do you think are the conclusions?
It is precisely this kind of common control that could help us to stop investing efforts in the formulation of laws, the reduction and improvement of limits, even if this does not have such a positive impact.
The savings economy means getting a suitable thing at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest price) to avoid enrichment and, eventually, criminal actions.
But not because the lowering of the limit on adjudications means that we are going to get it.
Perhaps because the system is saturated with so much "paperwork", those who want to look for flaws in the system will be able to do so more easily than if the limits were kept as high as they are now.
You speak of the problems in our country with the transfer of the legislation which regulates the practice of public procurement.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is it an office like our NKÚ or is it organized differently?
As for the offices, such as the NKÚ, there is the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors), with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only thing is that in their case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The powers are also to some extent analogous, but as Germany has a federal organization, the audit courts are even at this level.
The Federal Court of Accounts (BRH) can only control federal money, what we call state funds here.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, are controlled in Germany by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for the local law, is it simpler than ours?
I would not normally like to make a comparison without concrete data, but Germany is still a model in some respects, but it is not possible to say exactly where it is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
I'm sure you don't, but I repeat, I don't like to make these kind of comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries which we take as models have to face a great many problems.
