Šimon Ornest: We want to accumulate positive energy in our concerts
They say that in less than a month the world will end, what do you think about it?
It's just one of the many other scare stories we like to hang on to.
The Tap Tap band, we like to joke about this and we like to say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to postpone the end of the world or to prevent it.
In December, you're organizing a very original project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you explain that to our readers?
It's a state-run charity event that we've been planning for two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the end of the Mayan calendar set for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on December 20 at 9 p.m., we will organize 3 simultaneous concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end at approximately the same time as the Mayan calendar ends in the Pacific island nation of Kiribati, 12 hours ahead of our time zone.
Who came up with this idea?
It was my idea at first, then we all worked together with our designer Honza Augusta.
Besides wanting to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, we also want to reflect, together with society, on the state in which we will leave the world to our children.
To mark the end of the Mayan calendar we have also created a unique collection of items: boots, T-shirts, bags and original keychains against the end of the world which can be purchased at www.e-tap.cz, another way to support us.
The Tap Tap group, along with other performers, also sang the so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is titled "End of the world, cancelled".
It's currently very popular on YouTube, will it be heard at the benefit concerts?
Of course it is, and it's just gonna be the last one, well, as long as everything goes well and the world doesn't end...
It will be sung by all the performers at the same time in all three concerts.
The songs will be linked together simultaneously thanks to a special live broadcast on Czech Television.
Tomáš Hanák has written the lyrics of this song and plays the lead role of Jesus in the music video, where he also sings Xindl X...
How did this collaboration come about?
We even work together with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, besides organizing many charity events and concerts...
We are doing our best to participate in this project.
It has been shown that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the money raised from the concerts against the end of the world be used for?
A equipment for the educational center without barriers Studeo, which we have completed in its sixth consecutive year with the civil association Tap in Jedličkův ústav.
The pupils of Jedličkův ústav school are regularly visited by teachers with whom they engage in fun and interesting activities.
The students do not have the financial means to pay the teachers and we are making an effort to make this possible.
As part of the completion of the works at Jedličkův ústav, there will be a separate building to which we will move with this project.
Various groups and performers perform at each concert.
What are the selection criteria?
We try to make a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague there will be performances by Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
For more information, please refer to www.kpks.cz.
Do you have any other "spectacular action" planned in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the festival Pražské jaro, so here we will surely prepare an attractive program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I, personally, taking advantage of being in the United States, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap is, however, a group of people with disabilities.
What is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It's not as difficult as it might seem at first glance.
There are five members in electric wheelchairs, the chairs have to travel in the luggage compartment and also we carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well, and both the Czech Republic and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which continues to surprise me.
Even in Moscow, where we just returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad, you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you encountered so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have seen that, in the East, there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, so it is still not uncommon for a person to travel alone in an electric wheelchair through the city center.
Something as common as, for example, giving preference to someone in a wheelchair in an elevator, is not there.
Fortunately, a civil society association has been set up to try to raise awareness of the problems of people with disabilities.
In what ways should we follow the example of more developed countries?
There are many aspects in which we are behind...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and perfection of the situation always depends on the people directly affected.
In London and Madrid it is very normal for people with severe disabilities to move on their own in public and to be able to go to the toilet, to the museum, wherever they want...
But it is not very common for a large number of disabled people to participate actively in social life, in this respect, with The Tap Tap we are a little ahead!
A society that respects or has no barriers is one thing, but when the time comes for eminent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers to emerge, everything will begin to change for real.
So far, these are isolated cases of people with great willpower.
The Tap Tap is a very popular band right now, but if we look back a few years, what made you guys form the band in 1998?
I got into education at Jedličkův ústav, where I had a lot of young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I'm a musician, I play the saxophone, among other things, I started an amateur group with a co-worker.
And over time, as our moderator Lada Angelović says, it got a little out of hand.
However, the popularity didn't come until the last few years, or am I wrong?
It's true that connecting with famous singers and also actively working to promote the group helped us a lot.
We came to the conclusion that work that is not seen is as if it did not exist.
Thanks to the European Union's aid, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment, etc.
Did you really intend to go this far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning I saw the potential that there was, that you can do something differently.
The show business is full of things that look like each other.
It is logical, in its own way, that everything new is received with caution and takes a long time to be accepted.
There are few things extraordinary, but I dare say The Tap Tap is one of them.
The impression of someone who sees us for the first time is clearly compassion, it's a natural reaction...
But compassion is totally superfluous because disabled people are not abandoned beings who suffer and who should be pitied.
There are people who are capable of living a full life and developing, provided, of course, that they have the necessary means.
I always say that if something works out for people with disabilities, then it's not just an advance for them, but for the whole society.
Did the fact that you're a demanding boss, as many people describe you, help?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be rigorous in many respects and require a certain discipline.
I think it's completely normal.
Some people come with a romantic vision and their heads in the clouds and when they find out that they have to go to rehearsal for two days, go to the pre-test and spend a lot of time travelling and in concerts, the initial euphoria quickly leaves them.
But that's how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and get something done.
Currently the group The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there at the beginning of 1998?
Only one: Lada Angelovic.
We're an open group, people come in and out, you can't help it.
Whoever has the will and the will will always find the doors open
