Poland and the cosmos.
The meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency countries last week accepted Poland as the twelfth member of ESA.It is the second ESA member country from the former Eastern European bloc, after the Czech Republic, which became a full member on 12 November 2008.
Poland began intensive cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in the commissioning of ESA projects in the following years.
However, Poland's path to the cosmos began long before that.
Polish enthusiasts were already involved in spaceflight before World War II, although their work was not always understood.
I remember, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented his ideas on the pioneering study "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the assistants indifferent and, years later, Šternfeld recalled that Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the only one who had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The above-mentioned Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a major proponent of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a series of books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of cosmonautics, was known throughout the world and his contribution to science was rewarded when one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a dredge was built in Poland to be fitted with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown, and the details of the project are not known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the start of the dredge or for its braking.
Information about this dresina is limited to what is recorded in the press of the time.
From 1933 the Polish artillery began to devote itself to missiles.
The research was funded by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the material preserved, it is clear that the research reached the stage of practical tests.
However, with the arrival of German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 the prototype of a photoelectric fighter missile designed by the engineer Rohoziński appeared in the specialized press and the following year the study "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza", by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocki, was published.
Both projects were intended for the military use of missile engines.
Shortly before the war, the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all military missile engineering projects and coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the outbreak of war.
Other studies devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, the Society is first referred to with four very extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, by Prof. M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society that would be dedicated to cosmonautics was proposed.
At that time, projects for artificial satellites had already been launched and it was obvious that cosmic research was a discipline with future prospects.
Since early 1956 the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) aspired to become part of the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and in autumn of the same year the PTA became a full member.
The following year the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA participated significantly in the development of the sounding rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was a success and became the first Polish rocket on which scientific research was carried out.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and first flown on 10 October 1958.
The rocket had a peak of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm long and did not reach 5 kg weight.
Later, the RM-1A version was completed and in summer 1959 the two-stage RM-2 rockets began air tests in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was four feet, four inches long and weighed about 30 pounds.
Another type of rocket in development was to be the subject of real scientific study. The RM-34 rocket was to have a peak of 14.5 km and its mission was to control the high wind.
However, in 1962 the work was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1 rocket, which was built during the years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other by the space available for scientific apparatus.
The space available for the volume on the Meteor-1A was 0.4 litres, on the Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and on the Meteor-1C 0.62 litres.
The maximum in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aero Institute, whose first aerial tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg up to 60 km altitude.
Later versions were built, the Meteor-2H and the Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the formation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
Within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland joined the investigation of cosmic space on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remek.
