The MVRDV architecture studio shows that true adventures are not only in the head - in the example of the Spijkenisse library and the newly completed "mountain of books" - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, and there is something interesting to see at last", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company located near the library, points out: "Besides, the building is beautiful".
But I wonder why we need a library today.
We all have the Internet, tablets and e-books.
Nobody just walks into these old-fashioned libraries, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town on the outskirts of Rotterdam hardly worth a fleeting visit, has the dubious honor of having set a record that will be forgotten.
The population of 80,000 has the lowest literacy rate in the Netherlands.
To counteract this shameful situation, it was decided some years ago to make a contribution to the general culture by copying the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes in the form of decorated reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the educational offensive was limited.
And that's how the politicians decided that there was only one way to improve the statistics: a library had to be built!
Winy Maas, of the Dutch architecture firm MVRDV, a master in the art of bar diagrams and responsible for buildings that are both funny and cynical, took up the subject with his usual serenity and attended the presentation of the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury looked around in bewilderment and shrugged their shoulders, Maas proceeded to stack the books by size into a pyramid and concluded his brief speech with the following words: "Dear fellow citizens:
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse book mountain, the so-called 'Une Boekenberg'".
Nine years later, the mountain of 30 million euros rises in the intended place.
This is part of the revitalization project, which is completed with an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a couple of apartment and condominium buildings.
In early November the mountain of books was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project is also nominated for the "Dutch National Wood Award 2012".
In this way, the small town lacking history, which until now had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an incredibly ugly town hall behind whose white facade one would rather intuit a dairy plant, now has a work of contemporary architecture.
But above all, Spijkenisse now has its first public cultural building in its history.
The long road to the book
The first impression is that it is a paradise of books under a cheese.
True, there is an elevator that takes us right to the center of this mountain massif, but true space and reading lovers do not use it, preferring instead to merge with its topography at each step of their climb to the summit.
The fully glazed interior is bright and easy to see, the floors of brickwork and the elegant lanterns support the public status of the library.
The urban environment is perfect.
Looking up, you can see the park benches, the dogs, and the boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"The bookshelves are usually arranged along the facade, and in the center is a huge dark room, which is usually somewhat uncomfortable and impersonal", says Winy Maas.
What we've done is turn the classic spatial configuration upside down and take the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain is very well used: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental education center and the maintenance room.
Special mention should be made of the black shelves that simultaneously serve as wall cladding, parapet and rail.
The sight, the touch, the smell are strange.
Even the most up-to-date architects and civil engineers shake their heads when they hear about this unfamiliar material.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in the town of Spijkenisse.
And so one day, on a Frisian farm, we came across the right by-product from agriculture.
For many years, greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands have used a few millimetres thick plastic woven fabric as a base to hold the roots of crops.
It is a cheap and efficient material.
This fine fabric lasts two seasons and then is discarded.
For the library, this fabric was pressed, for the first time in such quantities, to four-centimeter-thick sheets.
With heat and pressure, so-called agricultural plastic (KLP) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells like a mix of new car and sneakers.
After 105 steps you reach the top of the mountain.
At the end of this continuous route of almost 500 meters around the mountain, the reward awaits us: from the cafeteria you not only have a fantastic view of the city, but you can also enjoy some tasty Dutch croquettes and their ficus planted in huge pots.
These create a pleasant atmosphere while maintaining the right atmospheric humidity for this mountain of literature.
Donations for a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but with its large glazed surfaces, this building is an example of ecological design", says Trouborst.
The necessary heating and cooling is obtained from geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a huge glass pyramid, even on the sunniest days the sun shines only for a few hours inside.
The huge wooden fences that run transversally across the glass façade provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
This creates a comfortable indoor climate.
The rest is up to the automatic shutters.
Stefan Spermon, the skeptical IT worker, has already dared to set foot in the new library.
And Lisette Verhaig has been there too.
The library has also been visited by Professor of Traditional Chinese Medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who describes the "Boekenberg" as the "late soul" of Spijkenisse.
The reason is that, on the occasion of the inauguration that took place a couple of weeks ago, all the inhabitants of the city were invited to donate a book from their private collection.
This is intended to fill, for the time being, the optical gaps of a library that does not yet have its complete archive; currently has 70,000 copies.
The concept has sunk deep.
The shelves are full.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Winy Maas.
"I think that thanks to our initiative now all the inhabitants have a certain link with this building.
Everyone knows that your book is part of the library.
Even if it's only there to adorn.
In this way, the MVRDV study has achieved a great success in this queen discipline which in the specialized jargon is known as "creation of an identity".
The town of Spijkenisse has written a piece of literary history.
No matter how young and uneducated he may be.
Finally a starting point for shaping your identity.
Szabo: 'Germans must play a more leading role'
Germany abstained from the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather precarious diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany indicated that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories UN observer state status.
However, Berlin ultimately abstained.
Why? Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that binds the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don't think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This has finally been declared by NATO.
Do you find it difficult for Germany to take a clear stand when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is.
This is because it is currently re-orienting its foreign policy away from a US-led policy, so to speak, and towards a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that the Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
Therefore, the Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to figure out what their role will be, but they have already started on the road towards a "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to that of countries like France or Britain.
What exactly does a 'normal' foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy which, when it comes to national interests, is prepared to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, that is to say, by exports and by relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are somewhat different from those of other great powers and Germany must therefore protect their interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken on the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
It must therefore be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion or Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I wouldn't put too much stock in it, because it's not a completely one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a key role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by abstaining in important decisions like the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position has a very high degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not think that there has been a break as drastic as in the case of Libya.
Perhaps Germany has earned a certain respect.
In the end, all this has done is to show that it is a country which is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly shown itself in favour of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the U.S. and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of American domestic policy.
I think that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it's obvious that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I think the real difference of opinion is not really as big as it is claimed to be.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he is developing.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogenous European policy, but that is not the case.
So they have no possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, simply because of its relationship with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of independent figure.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player?
Or is it still difficult for you to accept that leadership?
Germany has not yet got used to it, it is always a bit awkward and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that whenever Germany takes the lead, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
It's an old problem and nobody wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must show a receptive attitude towards the different neighbours and opinions and that is not easy.
The US influence in European politics is declining, but the EU is not filling the gap yet, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to take a more leading role.
Even if they don't like it, if they find it distasteful or if it makes them an even more unpopular people, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a fellow at the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
