Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Among the bacterial STDs are syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs of viral origin are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Sickles and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups of people affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhoea occur more frequently in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute takes as its basis that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis recorded in Germany originate in sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus), and gonorrhea.
HIV transmission among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, about 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This is a tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital sores, urinary discomfort, discharge, abdominal pain, and blisters or warts.
They often cause no pain or other symptoms and are therefore not detected.
How can one protect himself?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through infections by dirt and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical checkups, especially if you change sex partners frequently.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
