The Norwegian rakfisk: the world's most smelly fish?
The five million inhabitants of Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not just in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has something to do with its greed for a highly smelly fish?
Take a set of over-cured cheeses.
I put them in the middle of a mountain of wet, dirty football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowing, the scenery is spectacular, and that ever-present smell is in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how smelly you prefer it, up to a year.
As darkness falls and the weather turns colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
"You eat raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a shot", says Havard Halvarsen, the city's firefighter who is also known as the "Rakfisk General", who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking large amounts of the drink in one gulp.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk", says Havard.
The drink can kill the smell.
I'm trying some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it's not bad; it's not much different from a sushi portion that you've traveled a few miles on a bus.
Rakfisk is a product from a very different era, when poverty plagued Norway and, before refrigeration, fish was stored during the autumn in water and salt in hermetically sealed barrels.
Later, in the dead of winter, when it is well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactivated by alcohol, eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, mainly to the United States.
Today, the population is increasing rapidly; over 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of people from Sweden, the old rival and not so long ago richer than Norway, come to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered an important, essential, though rather smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be bought.
But, in fact, everything is expensive, a can of beer or a sandwich cost you a whopping 10 euros each.
Norway is not usually on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it that way.
Here people are still reluctant to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 incident".
It is very hard for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth lies the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we are doing so well", says Anna, our waitress, as she passes trays of rakfisk and who, with her long blonde mane and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, a prudent people".
His English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like to show off".
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution; all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was spending money they didn't have during the years leading up to the global financial crisis, Norway kept its wallet tight.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy", says Anna.
"And to eat rakfisk", he adds with a laugh.
I'm in the snow lining up to get something to eat; I've had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite juicy to savor.
But at night, that stinking fish comes back.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of the many venues that hold a rakfisk dinner where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A TV station has connected live with a host who wears a bow tie and is surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision song contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here is our score, Havard".
There's laughter and applause.
A man falls out of a chair, maybe overcome by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto is facing a rough start
