"I hope he is the same kind of president he was when he was governor", says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
Yet, that is precisely what the families of the Neza City victims fear most.
Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors are trying to address allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison.
The trial centers on Manning's time at the Quantico Military Prison in Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
Prosecutors sought to prove on Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to denounce the mistreatment he now claims he suffered while in military custody.
During the prosecution's cross-examination of Manning at a pretrial hearing at Fort Meade, Maryland, prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that the records of weekly visits by unit officers that Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he received.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing held following the defense's request that the case be dismissed given that his imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already been punishment enough, came a day after Manning testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was incarcerated in maximum security from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers would have asked Manning questions and noted his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment he received from the guards as "excellent" and the treatment he received at the facility in general as "very professional".
The forms show no complaint of ill-treatment, despite the officers asking Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein claimed.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had spoken of those problems and indicated to him that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
"They wrote 'no incidents' (after having spoken of the problems) but this does not necessarily mean that I had not mentioned any problems", Manning said.
Judge Army Colonel Denise Lind also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she was receiving during a January 2011 meeting with a board charged with examining the suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said they had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine and [I wanted] to be off injury prevention... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison located at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness in the heat.
He said that the fact that he wasn't allowed to know what was happening to him or what was going on in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to nothing but Camp Arafjon, to that cage", Manning explained Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage".
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, some flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, since it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light from outside pointing at his eyes while he slept.
He said that if the cellars couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's attorney filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about the treatment Manning was receiving.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about a plea he made in Thursday's statement, according to which, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell for one night, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of the jailers and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's cross-examination on Friday, Manning said he deduced from the order the guard gave him that he should drop the blanket he could have been covered with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before in an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning claimed that he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but that he had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, his flip-flops, and his glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his experiences in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he is convicted in the court martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges considered too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held under the rules applicable to any detainee in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperating with the enemy, illegally inducing the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If he's found guilty on all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American identity crisis
He claims that many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; he says they remind Mexicans of those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just come down the esplanade and reached the immigration processing area and I was already totally confused.
Some signs pointed the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and another for "Foreigners".
I stood there for a few seconds not sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I've been called Mexican my whole life.
It's about ethnic shorthand, in the same way that my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York refer to themselves as "Italian".
Later I settled on "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and I got in the foreigners' queue.
I thought of that moment this week when Mexico's president-elect, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda, as it always does when the leaders of these two countries meet, was immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was eager to talk also about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why it is now as likely that a Mexican will stay in Mexico as he will venture to the United States.
It wants to join the United States and Canada and create a trade bloc in North America in the style of the European Union.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting the drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of rancor.
Probably most Americans never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half its territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a US official says anything that involves the slightest criticism of Mexico, you start to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma are on the warpath.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that is really challenging is the relationship that they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans that live in the United States.
Are we talking about grudge?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason that there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, San Antonio is that, somewhere along our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or the mother or one of the grandparents, who was locked out of the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time, that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, low education, poor village background, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not to Mexico.
And even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican one.
Our identity may be unclear at times, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
Furthermore, we are aware that many of the Mexican elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look over our shoulders as if we're some sort of inferior category that isn't Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his eyes, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't be trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in America but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally as a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more about who they are and the latter are annoyed by it.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they're not part of either.
We love to listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also to Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of every country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, they see us as Americans.
And in the United States, we're considered Mexicans.
Now, to complicate things even further, from what I've learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would press political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, of course...
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much bad blood.
And with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us aren't so sure it's a great country.
I'm afraid you're gonna be left with this idea, fellas.
It's only fair.
If some Mexicans are still not ready to forgive the United States for the way it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful for the way their relatives were treated a long, long time ago.
I'm not sure.
Maybe we're more Mexican than I thought.
Old battles, new middle east
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that all hope is in vain.
Amidst the useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel's metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, even though the Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their long-standing conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in pieces, and Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in the regional turmoil, whether they like it or not.
Perhaps this makes their struggle even bloodier than before.
However, there is reason to believe that their lethal stalemate could be unravelled.
A War That Is Neither Lost Nor Won
At first sight, optimism seems very difficult to justify at present.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21st is maintained, this week's clashes have strengthened the hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, despite the fact that Gaza has been dealt a good beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and squeezing the 1.7 million people of Gaza into one of the most miserable and crowded corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to wipe out Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its implacable rivals in Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Furthermore, Hamas leaders may conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have been gaining influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced the Hamas cause, as has Qatar, one of the Gulf's richest and most dynamic states.
Exultant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is surrounding Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah-military party dominates, through Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels could topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
The growth of the Muslim Brotherhood in Egypt, led by President Muhammad Morsi, by far the most populous and fundamental of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region, especially in the southern flank of Israel.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, didn't have much time for Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is Hamas's cousin and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, Hamas may emerge as a player that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hard-liners will come to the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military issue is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
The Israelis will sleep better... for a while.
On the diplomatic front, the United States is more assertive than ever; many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
First of all, Israel has prospered, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
While rockets fired from Gaza have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had many suicide bombers, thanks in part to the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main chunk of territory aspiring to become a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to grow despite being illegal under international law.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even tougher group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to the January 22 elections, is in a good position.
Why spoil those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really governed the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets like their compatriots in Gaza?
Better to have them behind that wall and give them a good punch if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing will prevail, though the Arab Spring could alter their calculations.
Even if the Islamists who take over in Egypt and elsewhere do not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address the internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is greater than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the superpower in the area will hardly help the new Arab governments to improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to get the ceasefire is a good omen and could mark the beginning of something.
The Israelis should also think long term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, in the same way that this week a bus exploded in Tel Aviv.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demography is making the situation worse as the Arab population increases.
The brutal missions against Gaza every two or three years to repulse Hamas will pay an increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from people outside the conflict.
The solution is still the one that sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper are advocating: two states and the surrender of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to the outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must start to curb the flow of weapons into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented position to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
The Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to unite.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain a virtual state status in the UN.
Mr Obama also has an important role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Back in the White House, he seems equally reluctant to give it his full attention.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is of vital interest to the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
The generic tobacco packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and body parts with diseases appear on small, pale green boxes, which are the same for all brands of tobacco
The Australian Tobacco and Generic Packaging Act, a world-first, comes into force, replacing the logos and colours of the brands with a dim olive green wrapper, gruesome images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies who are sick from being the children of smoking parents.
Except for the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a type of small font.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The federal government of Australia claims that the goal is to deter youths from smoking by removing the traits that make smoking glamorous.
He relies on studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
"You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand", said federal health minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that showed, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry has put enormous pressure on the law.
Tobacco companies claimed that the law would encourage the black tobacco market, where cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
"The legislation will have serious unintended consequences", said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring more tobacco to sell on the streets of Australia.
Other people say that their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, claimed that demand for silicone cups and lids to cover up the unpleasant images on the cartons had skyrocketed from almost zero two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in the High Court of Australia.
Ms Ha claimed that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale establishments and that she was expecting more stock.
"It's good business for us".
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the target demographic.
Following a series of Australian laws banning television advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most retailers to keep cigarettes out of sight, tobacco marketing has shifted to online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Internet for local companies and websites, but it cannot restrict it on foreign websites.
"If you're a tobacco marketer and you're left with this small window to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be", said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman observed an increase in brand reviews from "ordinary citizens" posted on social media websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
It is questionable whether this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video or whether some marketing company is behind it all.
British American Tobacco of Australia indicated that the industry is focusing more on what the new regulations imply than on marketing.
The industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to object to the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that trade is being unfairly restricted, even though none of these countries have significant trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution by mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering similar laws on tobacco packaging.
In 2001 Canada became the first country to make it compulsory to include images in the boxes.
They are now mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
