On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating from the first century AD.
We also have to consider how we define boredom.
"The problem is that it has already been defined and discussed in a wide variety of ways", says John D. Eastwood, professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing published research and pitching the idea to a 100-person panel, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of "wanting, but not being able, to engage in a fulfilling activity".
He states that the difference between boredom and apathy is that the person is not doing something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do anything.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is "distracted attention, associated with low mood and a feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can sound awfully like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to view the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, whereas people who are depressed consider the problem to be their own.
Sometimes we think we're bored, when what happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups listened to a television program in the next room at a high volume that was completely unrelated, others listened to it at a low volume that was barely perceptible, while the third group did not listen to the audio at all.
The group that listened to the program at the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they had trouble concentrating, but they weren't sure why, and they attributed it to boredom.
"When you're trying to concentrate on a difficult or interesting task, the distraction can lead to boredom", said Mark J. Fenske, professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study's authors.
