There are people for whom their job is hell and others who literally work in hell.
Anto Wijaya is one of the 400 miners who earn their living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it must descend daily to the bottom of its crater, where sulphuric gas emanating from the bowels of the earth solidifies upon contact with air.
After picking up large stones of sulfur, weighing a total of about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets over his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only about 800 feet [250 m] to the top of the volcano, which rises to 8,000 feet [2,386 m], but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb in a turtle-like pace, keeping their balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall off the cliff.
