Unasur summit ends without making public the Lima Declaration
The 6th presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) concluded today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven attending leaders.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency said at the beginning that they were going to hand it over after the closure, but later said that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they noted that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during a brief statement to the press.
Access to information on the Summit was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the silent video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room with the message "private session, audio restricted".
The little information that circulated among the reporters was given by the press spokesmen of some of the governments of Unasur attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian one.
The only document released during the day was the list of assistant presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more data.
Subsequently, the Peruvian Presidency sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America-Arab Countries (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated.
The official website of ASPA confirms that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made efforts to ensure that there were secure transmission systems for all journalists but limited the information gathering to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (CIJ), which begins on Monday in The Hague to hear the allegations of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
"We will execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today", said Humala, along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that respects international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts", added Piñera, and greeted Humala with a handshake, alongside the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had accepted to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered gravely wrong.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after midday in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and action lines were fixed for 31 projects between South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence".
He informed that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to the internet at a low price in all corners of South America, and to address jointly and efficiently the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples", added Humala.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", said the Peruvian president in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five are related to Peru, and are located in the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve for its reincorporation into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and of good relations between neighbours, was another of the issues underlined by the summit.
In this regard, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully deal with the maritime dispute after a CIJ ruling, questioned by Bogotá.
"Tomorrow (Saturday) it is possible that I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We are going to review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega I hope to be able to tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico where they are scheduled to attend the takeover of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also, as part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the interim presidency of the regional bloc.
