Ratified by a United States court of appeals a ruling that ignores the restructuring of the debt of the Vitro Group achieved via a commercial tender in Mexico, the scenario sets a nefarious precedent for any national company with branches in the neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It would therefore be said that the survival guarantee procedures of the firms that are permitted by Mexican laws are not valid in the country of the bars and the stars, contrary to international conventions.
In practical terms, the backlash to the ruling issued on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless against the possibility of seizing their properties on the Bravo.
However, the ruling opens the door for the leading glass manufacturer in Mexico to go to the U.S. Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge in the case notes that the creditors must be governed by the United States Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New Orleans, says that the main procedure is the commercial bankruptcy processed in Mexico.
The first point would mean ignoring international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law was created for this purpose, with the American Law Institute as arbiter.
Secondly, the judgment states that without the intercompany vote, the debts of Vitro's subsidiaries to their parent companies being recognised in the critical mass of the commercial tender, the majority required to approve the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, the possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro's was not the first case where the scheme was accepted.
There are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts were endorsed by the Federal Institute of Mercantile Contracts.
What is certain, moreover, is that, subtracting the votes of the subsidiaries, in any case, the creditors of Vitro who fought against it in the US courts, that is to say the "butterfly" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot International and Liverpool Limited, will not have achieved a majority.
The vote would have been 45 percent to 37.
The Court of Appeal omits this.
From another angle, this one blames Vitro for the difficult situation it faced from 2008 onwards, apart from the serious economic crisis faced by the United States, hitting the country with the batons.
For now, the González Sada family will file a motion for reconsideration with the appeals court itself so that the vote reaches the full court, that is, the five magistrates, since only three voted.
If this does not succeed, the appeal of Cerciorare will be claimed, which requires the review of the process by a higher instance, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The seriousness of the case is that the court ignored a document sent by the government of Mexico under the figure of amicus curiae ("friend of the Court"), which details the procedure followed by Vitro under the framework of the Law of Mercantile Contests, noting that it was discharged with attachment to the agreements signed by both countries to match this with Chapter 15 of the Bankruptcy Law of the United States.
Furthermore, it is noted that the country adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules set for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee equity for debtors and creditors.
